dismissalComment.html: early breakthrough for England, and Monty Panesar has pulled off a run-out. Tendulkar drove wide of mid-off, but didn't time it and Panesar made a good sliding save, got his throw away quickly to Matt Prior. Ganguly was coming back for a second, but Tendulkar wasn't interested and Ganguly was caught a couple of inches short.

commentTextItems.html: and England bowl India out, Singh heaves across the to hand Panesar his first wicket

commentPostTextItems.html: That completes a fine all-round effort from England. Maiden centuries from Alastair Cook and Ian Bell set it up as England made 288, then James Anderson did the early damage with the new ball. Andrew Flintoff bowled well on his comeback, seven rapid and hostile overs, while Dimitri Mascarenhas finally picked up his first ODI wicket. For India it was a tough day. The fielding was poor and the batting didn't fire under lights. But there are six games left so plenty of time claw things back. The next outing is at Bristol, on Friday, and it's another day/night match. Please join us then but for now, from Andrew McGlashan and George Binoy, it's goodnight from Cricinfo.
